Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Written by
Author: Edgar Allan Poe
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/20/2026
Notes: Gothic period live-action; candlelight, deep shadows, one continuous medium throughout. NARRATOR is a pale, gaunt man of middle years, hollow dark eyes, thin lips, dark disordered hair, plain black 1840s coat and waistcoat. OLD MAN is frail, white-haired, in a nightshirt; his left eye is a pale blue vulture eye filmed over with a dull veil. Three POLICE OFFICERS in dark period coats and badges.

FADE IN:

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

A single candle. The NARRATOR sits close to us, addressing the lens. Sweat at his temples. Hands steady—too steady.

NARRATOR
True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how calmly I can tell you the whole story.

He leans in a fraction.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once conceived, it haunted me day and night.

INT. OLD HOUSE - HALL OUTSIDE CHAMBER - NIGHT

Candlelight along warped boards. The NARRATOR stands before a closed door, staring at the latch. Beyond, faint breathing.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Object there was none. Passion there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

The OLD MAN asleep in bed. One pale blue eye—filmed, vulture-like—catches a thread of light and seems to stare even shut.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I think it was his eye! yes, it was this! He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye, with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold; and so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

The NARRATOR, on camera again, almost smiling.

NARRATOR
Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to work!

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - DAY

Morning. The NARRATOR throws open shutters, hearty, kind. The OLD MAN sits up, blinking the filmed eye.

NARRATOR
I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week before I killed him.

He clasps the Old Man's shoulder, voice warm.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
And how have you passed the night?

The Old Man murmurs a sleepy reply. The Narrator smiles.

INT. HALL OUTSIDE CHAMBER - NIGHT

Midnight. The NARRATOR turns the latch—oh, so gently. A DARK LANTERN, fully closed, in his hand. He opens the door a hand's width and thrusts the lantern in, then his head, moving inch by inch.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And every night, about midnight, I turned the latch of his door and opened it—oh, so gently! And then, when I had made an opening sufficient for my head, I put in a dark lantern, all closed, closed, that no light shone out, and then I thrust in my head.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - CONTINUOUS

His head inside the black room. He eases the lantern open a crack. A single thin ray seeks the bed.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed. Ha!—would a madman have been so wise as this?

The ray finds only a closed lid. The filmed eye is shut.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And this I did for seven long nights—every night just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - DAY

Again morning. The NARRATOR enters boldly.

NARRATOR
Good morning! How have you passed the night?

The OLD MAN answers without suspicion. The Narrator laughs under his breath as he leaves.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
So you see he would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect that every night, just at twelve, I looked in upon him while he slept.

INT. HALL OUTSIDE CHAMBER - NIGHT

The eighth night. The NARRATOR's fingers on the latch move slower than a watch's minute hand. Triumph tightens his face. He chuckles—soft, involuntary.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the door. A watch's minute hand moves more quickly than did mine. Never before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my sagacity. I could scarcely contain my feelings of triumph.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - CONTINUOUS

Pitch black. Shutters fastened. The door creeps wider. On the bed, the OLD MAN suddenly shifts—startled.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I fairly chuckled at the idea; and perhaps he heard me; for he moved on the bed suddenly, as if startled. Now you may think that I drew back—but no. His room was as black as pitch with the thick darkness, and so I knew that he could not see the opening of the door, and I kept pushing it on steadily, steadily.

The Narrator's head is in. His thumb slips on the tin fastening of the lantern—

A tiny metallic scrape.

The OLD MAN springs up in bed.

OLD MAN
Who's there?

Silence. The Narrator does not move. Does not breathe.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR
I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

The OLD MAN upright in the dark, listening. The NARRATOR frozen in the doorway, head inside, lantern shut.

A slight groan—low, stifled—from the bed.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Presently I heard a slight groan, and I knew it was the groan of mortal terror. It was not a groan of pain or of grief—oh, no!—it was the low stifled sound that arises from the bottom of the soul when overcharged with awe. I knew the sound well.

The Old Man's breathing quickens. He whispers to himself.

OLD MAN
(whispered)
It is nothing but the wind in the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor... It is merely a cricket which has made a single chirp.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Yes, he had been trying to comfort himself with these suppositions: but he had found all in vain. All in vain; because Death, in approaching him had stalked with his black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim.

A long hold. The Old Man still does not lie down. The Narrator's eye gleams in the crack of the door.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
When I had waited a long time, very patiently, without hearing him lie down, I resolved to open a little—a very, very little crevice in the lantern.

His fingers work the tin. Stealthy. A single dim ray, like the thread of a spider, shoots out and falls full upon the vulture eye.

It is open—wide, wide open.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It was open—wide, wide open—and I grew furious as I gazed upon it. I saw it with perfect distinctness—all a dull blue, with a hideous veil over it that chilled the very marrow in my bones; but I could see nothing else of the old man's face or person: for I had directed the ray as if by instinct, precisely upon the damned spot.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

The NARRATOR's face tightens; he almost presses into the lens.

NARRATOR
And have I not told you that what you mistake for madness is but over-acuteness of the sense?—now, I say, there came to my ears a low, dull, quick sound, such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. I knew that sound well, too. It was the beating of the old man's heart.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

The ray fixed on the open filmed eye. SOUND: a muffled, quick tattoo—soft at first, then growing.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It increased my fury, as the beating of a drum stimulates the soldier into courage.

The NARRATOR holds still. Barely breathes. The heartbeat LOUDER. Quicker.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But even yet I refrained and kept still. I scarcely breathed. I held the lantern motionless. Meantime the hellish tattoo of the heart increased. It grew quicker and quicker, and louder and louder every instant.

His hand trembles on the lantern. The sound fills the black room.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The old man's terror must have been extreme! It grew louder, I say, louder every moment!—do you mark me well? And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to uncontrollable terror. Yet, for some minutes longer I refrained and stood still.

A neighbour's wall—thin. The beat pounds. The Narrator's eyes widen with a new fear.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But the beating grew louder, louder! I thought the heart must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by a neighbour! The old man's hour had come!

With a loud YELL he throws open the lantern—light floods—and leaps into the room.

The OLD MAN shrieks once—once only.

The Narrator drags him to the floor and pulls the heavy bed over him. Silence of struggle, then stillness beneath the mattress.

The Narrator stands over the overturned bed and smiles gaily.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I then smiled gaily, to find the deed so far done.

SOUND: the heart still beats—muffled, under the bed. Many minutes. The Narrator listens, head tilted, patient, almost gentle. He does not move.

The muffled beat... and beat... and beat...

At last it ceases.

He removes the bed. Kneels. Places his hand upon the Old Man's heart and holds it there. Waiting. Many minutes more. No pulsation.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Yes, he was stone, stone dead. I placed my hand upon the heart and held it there many minutes. There was no pulsation. He was stone dead. His eye would trouble me no more.

INT. BARE ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

The night wanes. The NARRATOR works hastily, in silence. A tub stands ready. We see enough: the saw, the dismembered shape, the careful hands—head, arms, legs.

He pries up three planks from the flooring, deposits the remains between the scantlings, replaces the boards. Smooths the seams. No stain. He glances at the tub and laughs under his breath.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I then replaced the boards so cleverly, so cunningly, that no human eye—not even his—could have detected any thing wrong. There was nothing to wash out—no stain of any kind—no blood-spot whatever. I had been too wary for that. A tub had caught all—ha! ha!

A distant BELL sounds four.

INT. STREET DOOR - NIGHT

Still dark. A KNOCKING at the street door. The NARRATOR goes down with a light heart and opens it.

Three men—FIRST OFFICER, SECOND OFFICER, THIRD OFFICER—stand on the threshold in dark coats, badges catching the candlelight. Perfect suavity.

FIRST OFFICER
A shriek was heard by a neighbour during the night. Suspicion of foul play has been aroused. We are officers of the police—deputed to search the premises.

The Narrator smiles.

NARRATOR
Gentlemen—welcome.

INT. OLD HOUSE - VARIOUS ROOMS - NIGHT

He leads them through with easy hospitality—hall, sitting room, stairs—candle raised.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I smiled,—for what had I to fear? I bade the gentlemen welcome.

NARRATOR
The shriek you heard was my own—in a dream. The old man is absent in the country.

He gestures them on.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
Search—search well.

INT. OLD MAN'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

He leads them in. Shows the undisturbed bed, the treasures, the neat room. In the enthusiasm of confidence he brings chairs and sets them out.

NARRATOR
Rest from your fatigues.

He places his own chair precisely upon the boards beneath which the corpse is hidden—and sits.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
In the wild audacity of my perfect triumph, I placed my own seat upon the very spot beneath which reposed the corpse of the victim.

The three officers sit. They are satisfied. They chat of familiar things. The Narrator answers cheerily.

FIRST OFFICER
A quiet street, this.

SECOND OFFICER
Once the neighbour is calmed, our work is done.

THIRD OFFICER
You keep a tidy house.

NARRATOR
I thank you.

Ere long his face pales. He touches his temple.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But, ere long, I felt myself getting pale and wished them gone. My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my ears: but still they sat and still chatted.

A RINGING—faint—then more distinct. He talks more freely.

NARRATOR
The neighbourhood is most peaceful. We have never had trouble—never—

The ringing gains definiteness. His eyes shift.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The ringing became more distinct:—it continued and became more distinct: I talked more freely to get rid of the feeling: but it continued and gained definiteness—until, at length, I found that the noise was not within my ears.

SOUND: a low, dull, quick sound—such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. From under the floorboards. From under his chair.

He goes very pale. Talks more fluently, voice heightened.

NARRATOR
—and the markets of late, you will have noticed, are—

The heartbeat grows. The officers chat on, pleasant, smiling. They do not seem to hear.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
No doubt I now grew very pale;—but I talked more fluently, and with a heightened voice. Yet the sound increased—and what could I do? It was a low, dull, quick sound—much such a sound as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. I gasped for breath—and yet the officers heard it not.

He talks more quickly, more vehemently. Rises. Argues about trifles in a high key, violent gesticulations.

NARRATOR
—trifles, sir, mere trifles—the weather, the hour, the absurdity of alarm—

The noise steadily increases.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Why would they not be gone?

He paces the floor with heavy strides. Foams. Raves. Swings his chair and grates it upon the boards—wood SCREECHING—but the heartbeat rises over all.

Louder—louder—louder.

The officers chat pleasantly and smile.

FIRST OFFICER
You seem unwell.

SECOND OFFICER
Perhaps some water.

The Narrator stares at their calm faces. The beat is thunder.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God!—no, no! They heard!—they suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror!—this I thought, and this I think. But anything was better than this agony! Anything was more tolerable than this derision! I could bear those hypocritical smiles no longer! I felt that I must scream or die! and now—again!—hark! louder! louder! louder! louder!

He breaks—shrieking, pointing at the floor beneath their feet.

NARRATOR
Villains! dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!

The officers spring up. The heartbeat POUNDS. The Narrator's finger stabs the boards over the grave.

FADE OUT.

THE END
